## Unit Tests ##

## ⚠️ Important: Do Not Write Tests Unprompted

**Never write, add, or modify unit tests unless the user explicitly asks for them.**

This includes:
- Do not add tests when implementing new features or components
- Do not add tests when fixing bugs
- Do not suggest adding tests as a follow-up step unless asked
- Do not update existing tests unless explicitly requested

Only write tests when the user's request clearly and directly asks for them (e.g. "write a test for...", "add test coverage for...").

############

# Documentation
Whenever making updates in this app be in the mindset that a different LLM or developer may need to come and make updates to this app later. So always document your work in the appropriate files in the .builder/rules files. To create/update a rules file for Builder's AI:

Create a .mdc file within the .builder/rules/ directory or update an existing one as appropriate. Provide a sensible name for your file and provide the metadata as shown below.

# example of a .builder/rules/ file
# .builder/rules/component-structure.mdc
---
description: Component structure
globs:
alwaysApply: false
---
<add whatever documentation is needed>

############################

The following options are available as keys within the metadata header:

description: a brief description of the file's rules
globs: specific file paths where these rules should apply
alwaysApply: if set to true, the AI always applies these rules; otherwise, the AI contextually decides when to apply the rules
** You should use alwaysApply:false unless it's a rule that should be sent to the LLM no matter what you are working on. Very few files should be always apply.
